TY  - JOUR
T1  - Yahoo! for Amazon: Sentiment Extraction from Small Talk on the Web
AU  - Das, Sanjiv R.
AU  - Chen, Mike Y.
Y1  - 2007/09/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1070.0704
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1070.0704
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1375
EP  - 1388
VL  - 53
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Extracting sentiment from text is a hard semantic problem. We develop a methodology for extracting small investor sentiment from stock message boards. The algorithm comprises different classifier algorithms coupled together by a voting scheme. Accuracy levels are similar to widely used Bayes classifiers, but false positives are lower and sentiment accuracy higher. Time series and cross-sectional aggregation of message information improves the quality of the resultant sentiment index, particularly in the presence of slang and ambiguity. Empirical applications evidence a relationship with stock values?tech-sector postings are related to stock index levels, and to volumes and volatility. The algorithms may be used to assess the impact on investor opinion of management announcements, press releases, third-party news, and regulatory changes.
AB  - Extracting sentiment from text is a hard semantic problem. We develop a methodology for extracting small investor sentiment from stock message boards. The algorithm comprises different classifier algorithms coupled together by a voting scheme. Accuracy levels are similar to widely used Bayes classifiers, but false positives are lower and sentiment accuracy higher. Time series and cross-sectional aggregation of message information improves the quality of the resultant sentiment index, particularly in the presence of slang and ambiguity. Empirical applications evidence a relationship with stock values?tech-sector postings are related to stock index levels, and to volumes and volatility. The algorithms may be used to assess the impact on investor opinion of management announcements, press releases, third-party news, and regulatory changes.
